<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix</i> <i>hookeriana</i>, <i>Salix</i> <i>sitchensis</i> and/or <i>Spiraea</i> <i>douglasii</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the tall shrub or low tree canopy with <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Cornus</i> <i>sericea</i>, <i>Lonicera</i> <i>involucrata</i>, <i>Morella</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Rubus</i> spp., <i>Salix</i> <i>lasiolepis</i>, <i>Sambucus</i> <i>nigra</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. As a shrubland, emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Acer</i> <i>macrophyllum</i>, <i>Alnus</i> <i>rubra</i>, <i>Picea</i> <i>sitchensis</i>, <i>Populus</i> <i>trichocarpa</i>, <i>Pseudotsuga</i> <i>menziesii</i> or <i>Salix</i> <i>lucida</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 8 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Salix hookeriana</i> > 50% relative cover (Sawyer et al. 2009).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix sitchensis</i> is > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy with <i>Salix lasiolepis</i> and <i>Rubus</i> spp. (Klein et al. 2015).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix hookeriana </i>and/or <i>Salix sitchensis</i> >30% relative cover in the shrub canopy with <i>Salix lasiolepis, Morella californica, Rubus</i> spp. and other shrubs (Buck-Diaz et al. 2020).</li>
		
		<li><i>Salix sitchensis</i> is > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy, or > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy with <i>Salix lasiolepis</i> (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
		<li><i>Spiraea douglasii</i> is > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Christy 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Coastal streams, tidal swamps, riparian areas, and areas near the ocean where water stands and seasonally floods as in deflation plains and swales among stabilized dunes, lagoon margins, and floodplains. Soils are alluvial and often mucky. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Salix hookeriana</i> as a FACW plant, and <i>Salix sitchensis</i> as a FACW plant, and <i>Spiraea douglasii</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
