<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix hookeriana</i> and <i>Salix sitchensis </i>were treated in separate alliances in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, Second Edition</i>. They are now merged into this combined alliance.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Salix hookeriana </i>is a riparian tree or shrub that attains 8 m in height. Its leaves are elliptic to widely ovate with densely hairy undersurfaces. It is sometimes confused with <i>S. lasiolepis, </i>but <i>S. hookeriana </i>typically has wider leaves and hairy stems. It blooms and fruits in early spring. The wind-dispersed seed is viable for a few days. Germination is best on fine-grained, moist, bare soil. Established plants tolerate seasonal inundation. <i>S. hookeriana </i>sprouts from a root crown in lighted conditions. Seedling establishment is high if seasonal and moisture requirements are met (Reed 1993a). The species occurs in California as individuals to 1000 m in the North Coast Ranges and Klamath Mountains (Argus 1997), well outside the range of the alliance.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Salix sitchensis </i>is a deciduous shrub that attains 7 m. Twigs are brown and covered with white hairs. Leaf blades are lanceolate to obovate, green above, and white silky-haired below. Plants produce large quantities of wind-dispersed seeds. Seeds are not dormant and remain viable for only a few days. They germinate rapidly on moist soil. Plants will sprout from their root crown or stem base after fire or cutting. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Spiraea douglasii</i> is a deciduous, rhizomatous, riparian shrub that is moderately sized at 3-6 feet tall and spreads through clonal growth and seed dispersion via animals. <i>S. douglasii</i> readily resprouts from rhizomes and root crown after disturbance such as fire (Esser 1995c).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Salix sitchensis </i>and <i>S. hookeriana</i> are typical dominants or co-dominants in this alliance, and stands range from Alaska to California. These species are ecologically and morphologically similar. They both grow along low elevation streams and lagoons along the North Coast of California. Many willow stands observed from Mendocino Co. north are dominated by <i>S. hookeriana</i>, while other stands both north of Mendocino Co. and further south at least to San Luis Obisbpo Co. are dominated by <i>S. sitchensis </i>. Stands commonly occur in road banks and along shores of creeks, rivers, lagoons, and dune hollows. It is the major willow scrub along the moist, northwestern coastal belt of California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
