    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p><i>Salix hookeriana</i> occurs throughout the Northern California Coast (263A). <i>Salix sitchensis </i>occurs in the Northern California Coast (263A) and Central California Coast (261A).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands of <i>Salix sitchensis</i> occur sporadically along drainages and draws at or close to the coast in San Mateo Co. (Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). Many stands occur near Eureka and Crescent City. On Humboldt Bay’s North Spit and at Clam Beach, stands occur as woody swales with <i>Juncus breweri </i>in the understory (Parker 1974, Duebendorfer 1989). A dense willow stand sampled at Dry Lagoon occurs adjacent to coastal strand vegetation, and it had a well developed understory that included <i>Maianthemum dilatatum </i>and <i>Gaultheria shallon </i>(CVIS 2007). Stands also exist in Point Arena - Stornetta Unit of the California Coastal National Monument and MacKerricher State Park in Mendocino Co., sometimes solely dominated by <i>S. sitchensis </i>or <i>Salix hookeriana </i>and other times co-dominating with <i>Alnus</i> or other <i>Salix </i>spp. (Buck-Diaz et al. 2020). Stands also appear further south including on Point Reyes Peninsula near McClure’s Beach, in Marin Co., with <i>S. sitchensis</i> dominant (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Willows including <i>Salix hookeriana </i>are effective at bank stabilization and are readily useful for stream restoration projects. <i>Spiraea douglasii</i> is sensitive to soil compaction (Esser 1995c). </div>
</div>

    

    

